Its comments were made in reference to an attack on a female advocate in Johannesburg last week by people wearing Black First Land First (BLF) T-shirts. “Although we accept the right of political entities and members of the public to protest, violence and destruction can never be condoned,” said LSSA co-chairpersons Mvuzo Notyesi and Ettienne Barnard. The law society said assault was a criminal offence and it urged authorities to investigate the matter urgently and to “bring the perpetrators to book”. 